story:
First of all, a big thank you for supporting my fundraising!

I’m going to be challenging myself to climb to the summit of Mount Snowdon on the 15th of May 2021, in order to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support and in memory of my dad who sadly lost his life to cancer 3 years ago. My dad was diagnosed with cancer back in December 2015 and fought a tough battle for 2 years before sadly then being given 6 months to live. Macmillan provided my dad and the family with remarkable end of life support in the comfort of his own home and were always there for absolutely ANYTHING. 

I can’t even begin to explain how this affected me and how I’ve struggled to come to terms with the loss of such a significant person at such an early stage of my own life. Those who know me will know I’m not physically fit by any means so this will be a big challenge for me and hopefully will lead onto challenging myself even further and raising more vital funds for an incredible charity. I feel it’s now my time to give something back to the people that provide the expert support and most importantly to say thank you for everything they did for him.

At Macmillan, they give people with cancer everything they’ve  got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are their worries. But without your help they can’t support everyone who needs them. story:
During March 2021, I’ll be running 5 kilometres every day (155km) in order to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support. Those close to me will know about the fight my Dad has had with cancer over the last couple of years,  I’d love to be able to raise some money for a brilliant charity who provide support for families like my own. 

I’m proud to say that my employer Barclays will match what I raise up to £1000.00 where a name is left with a donation.

Please share my page with others and donate what you can.

I’ve never ran for more than 7 consecutive days, nor have I ran over 120  kilometres in a month, so I hope my knees are up for the challenge!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
In 2006, I sadly lost my amazing dad to a heart attack.

Since he passed away, tests have shown I have the hereditary form of high cholesterol (Familial Hypercholesterolaemia), and am, therefore, also at risk of heart disease. Which also means that, unfortunately, so are my children.

I'm lucky that my condition was picked up early enough to embark on a lifetime of medication, monitoring and hospital appointments. And from next month, my kids will be tested to see if they have also inherited the same condition.

It took something as extreme as my dad passing away, to alert me to this "silent" condition. Without that happening, I'd have been completely unaware.

The BHF were also an invaluable source of help and support to my lovely father in law, following his heart attacks and subsequent heart surgery, two years ago. Again, another man who never realised he was unwell until the unthinkable happened.

I am raising money for the British Heart Foundation to hopefully bring awareness to these hidden conditions.

Now, you all know I'm a raging chocoholic, so this is going to be very very tough for me! Hardly a day passes where I don't consume chocolate in some form, so I'm gonna be going cold turkey and will really need your support!

But as difficult as it'll be, I'm sure it won't do me any harm to stay off the sweet stuff for a few weeks, and I'm looking forward to seeing and feeling the benefits.

It would mean the world to me if you could donate to my cause. Even just a little bit will do!

Thank you so much.

Em xxx

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
This is an important cause to me having my own parents suffer with heart attacks themselves luckily they survived these but I’ve also lost family to heart disease also- my lovely grandad Bill Ashbridge who also suffered with angina and my Dad (step) Mark Harrison losing him to HOCUM far too early aged 45.

So to make it a challenge as I’ve done 2 of these in previous years 1st giving up choc and 2nd choc and sweets! 

This time for the whole month of March I’m giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks. I’m really hope you will help encourage me on this challenge and possibly donate, anything helps! You maybe think well we won’t know if she cheats well if you know me, that would never happen not when I’m doing it for such a good cause and I can show my girls too! 

Thanks for taking the time To read

Much love katy

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I’m taking part in DeChox and not eating any chocolate or sweets for the month of March. I have Familial Hypercholestroleamia and want to raise awareness. A huge 1 in 250 people have it and a lot sadly don’t even know they have it! If it’s left untreated it can cause early age stroke, heart attack and heart disease. Therefore I’ve been on statins for yonks. It’s a condition you have from birth, whether you have a ‘healthy’ diet or not. There’s 50% chance that I’ve passed it on to my boys and they too may need statins. I’m on a loose weight and be happy / healthy mission, so cutting out chocolate and sweets is a needed step. 

BHF says - The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I am giving up chocolate and anything sweet for a whole month to raise money in memory of my wonderful grandad Eddie who sadly passed away on 7th February this year. 

Several years ago, he needed a triple heart bypass and thanks to the wonderful work of all the doctors, nurses and the BHF he had the surgery and it gave him a new lease of life  enabling him to continue living life to the full, spending time with family and friends and getting to meet and enjoy his two great grandchildren. Without the BHF none of this would have been possible. 

Grandad had a sweet tooth too, especially for a bounty so he knows how hard this will be. If anyone can donate anything at all we would be eternally grateful, this really is going to be a challenge, but a very worth while one to raise money in memory of an incrediably special man. 

Thank you xx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, that means if 24 people donate £1 it helps significantly. Hopefully you will consider the offer to make a small contribution and aid the research that may affect you or your family at some stage in their lives. 

As a cardiology nurse I care for those with different conditions, acute and chronic. This has provided me the knowledge of the importance of research with treatments. Research so far over the years has allowed us to enhance treatment and improve quality and quantity of life as people are living for longer, but it is still a battle we are fighting. Due to Covid-19 funding for research has reduced to put more funding into developing a vaccine for the population, although it is beneficial to humanity unfortunately has greatly reduced the progress for other areas. I work closely with the specialist nurses that aid the support of those with heart failure, congenital diseases, valve diseases and coronary disease, the treatment we currently have is great but it could and CAN get better.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
From me ... The idea of giving up chocolate and sweets for a month is already making me nervous, I'm a total chocoholic,  but this is such a great cause.

I still remember the pain I felt when my Dad suffered a heart attack while we were on holiday in Turkey in 2002. Although after surgery he made a fulll recovery he still needs regular check ups. 

For him and anyone else that has suffered a heart attack I want to raise what I can for BHF . If the information and support they provide can stop just one person facing the same nightmare then giving up chocolate will be worth it!!!!

From them .... the pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi lovelies, I’m on a mission to raise money for the British Heart Foundation for reasons very close to mine and my families hearts and in particular in memory of my grandad who we miss and love dearly. He like many became an angel far to soon, but we can try help the British Heart Foundation keep more loved ones hearts beating. Share the love ❤️

I’m taking up the challenge to not eat or drink anything chocolate, any sweets or fizzy drinks for 31 days... yes a whole month! Now anyone that knows me well knows I cannot be without my chocolate and there has been no period in my life where I haven’t not had anything chocolate within a month... this is going to be a real challenge especially with boredom striking in this current lockdown situation so come support me and my waistline whilst raising money for a fantastic charity! Let’s do this! ❤️❤️❤️

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: After losing my Dad last year to a sudden Heart ❤️ attack I have decided to take part in this fundraiser for a cause which means so much to me. Due to the pandemic funding has been cut by half, and many people are not getting the treatment they need until it’s too late. I’d like to help raise money for the continued research into one of the biggest killers we face. And although it may be too late for my Dad it may help other families in the future.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Anyone who knows me, knows I'm the biggest chocoholic going. I'm also coeliac so my food intake is very limiting so giving up another food thing is a big thing for me.

Chocolate is my comfort. It's the one thing I know I can go to and it gives me a boost. I'd give up alcohol before chocolate 🤦🏼‍♀️

I'd like to raise as much money as I can for The British Heart Foundation as this year is my 10 year anniversary from having a heart operation for Wolff Parkinson Syndrome.

So I'm Giving up chocolate for 31 days this March 2021 to raise money for life saving research and be part of a movement to beat heartbreak forever.

story:

Please give what you can and help me raise money for the British Heart Foundation.


Thank you.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I have pledged to give up chocolate throughout March. I know it won’t sound like much of a challenge to some people, but it’s going to be so tough for me. I love chocolate and I eat it every day. I can’t resist a bar of Galaxy Caramel, a bag of chocolate buttons, a slice of chocolate fudge cake or a mug of hot chocolate. I’m not really sure what I’m going to eat instead!

I’m more worried about this than I have been about some of my running challenges, but hopefully knowing I’m helping a good cause will keep me going. A few years ago I had tests for what turned out to be a harmless heart murmur, but it was terrifying to think there could be something wrong with my heart. The British Heart Foundation offers a lot of support for people with problems with their heart and needs help more than ever due to the pandemic. 

I’ll be donating money I haven’t spent on chocolate at the end of the month, but I’d love it if you could consider supporting both me and the British Heart Foundation by making a donation. Thank you so much.

story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Anyone who knows me knows that I am a complete Chocoholic! It is definitely the hardest thing for me to quit. 

I wanted to take part in BHFs Dechox event in memory of my amazing Dad and hope to raise £50.

I'll be incredibly grateful for even the smallest of donations.

Thank you xx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: The Covid pandemic has cut both government funding and fundraising which enables the BHF to build on their research. I have lost my Mum, baby brother and my paternal grandad to heart conditions. My youngest daughter has a congenital heart condition that needs monitoring. One way for me to help is to give up chocolate and sweets for the whole of March. Going to be tough because it will be Mothering Sunday and my birthday halfway through. Please give what you can.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Do you want to help in a good cause supporting the British Heart Foundation in life saving research? If yes, then read on! 

Chocoholics unite! Give up chocolate, or more, for 31 days in March to raise money for life saving research and be part of a movement to beat heartbreak forever. Every pound you raise will help fund vital research into heart and circulatory diseases with the British Heart Foundation ❤ 


My middle name should be chocoholic, I indulge in that much of the tasty stuff. And if I can curb the appetite thru a Dechox to raise awareness and support lifesaving research for 31 days throughout March, then I'll give it my best shot.

Thank you for your support. 

Much love 💜

Dechox 2021


www.justgiving.com

story:
Myself , Ruby and Olivia are taking part in this years dechox where we will be giving up chocolate ! We have chosen to raise money for BHF as their vital research helps save lives including our very own Papa Chaff. I know this year has been tough so no need to make a donation if you can’t,  a share of our fundraiser will also be a great show of support ! 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
In memory of my Dad who passed away suddenly in 2013; I have signed up for Dechox.  I will be giving up all sweets, chocolate and fizzy drinks for the whole of March.

If you know me / my diet then you will realise what a challenge this is going to be.... I literally don't know what I am going to eat and drink for a month!!

In these crazy times, I know money is tight for many but even if you can just spare £1 for British Heart Foundation it would be extremely appreciated.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: WALK A MILLION MILES FOR ONE OF THEM SMILES
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

I think if more people were aware what to look out for Heart Failure my wonderful Mum would still be here now. 

I would say soon as you see any kind of symptons, act quick, don't keep putting it off to get checked, leaving it could stop you having the life saving surgery you may need.

Throughout the month I will be doing awareness on my page for this awful disease.
title: Walk 10k a day + no choc, crisps or Bread. Whole of March.
pageSummary: I want to raise money and awareness because I want to do it in memory of Mum

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
On Monday 22/02/21 Alisse starts her
Tour De France Bicycle Challenge.
She is going to try and cycle 100km / 62miles in a month, she’s going to do some fund raising at the same time for a cause that is very close to our hearts.

As you all know we sadly lost mum in November 2020 due to a major problem in her Heart. So to help towards vital research the money raised by Alisse will go straight to them. We would love it if people would sponsor Alisse just 1p per kilometre (£1 in total for the 100km covered)
Thank you all so much 🤍💛❤️

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story: After several months of recurrent chest infections and my asthma becoming more problematic than ever, I decided after talking to my asthma doctor, to start walking everyday. I am hoping to improve my peakflow, my fitness, my weight, my heart & my head! ❤ Six days in I saw this on a friends Facebook page and thought what better way to make these changes for myself than to help others whilst I do so! ❤🥰 So here is my fundraising page. Thank you so much in advance for your donations. Let's try to make a difference for as many people as possible. ❤❤❤

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation. 

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. 

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society. 

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story:
Great Ormond Street Hospital Childrens Charity (GOSH Charity) and McColls, the leading neighbourhood retailer, are delighted to announce a brand-new charity partnership that aims to raise £1million over the next three years.

Seriously ill children from across the UK travel to Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) for specialist treatment for rare and complex conditions.

The money raised by McColls will help fund GOSH Charitys vital parent accommodation service, supporting the refurbishment of 'McColl's House', which brings families closer together when a child is receiving treatment.

By partnering with GOSH Charity, McColls colleagues and customers will support families at the heart of their communities, right across the UK.

story:
I have registered to complete the Cotswold Way Ultra Challenge 2021.  This involves jogging, and probably lots of walking, 100km inside 20 hours.  It is on Saturday 26th June, starting and finishing in Cirencester. 

I have chosen to support Great Ormond Street Hospital Children’s Charity. 

As most of you know, this charity is close to my heart.  Not only did they perform life saving surgery on my daughter, but they continue to provide her with the best care year on year. She has had 12 surgeries to date, and countless outpatient appointments and after care.  She will be receiving care there until she is 18.  

Since December 2019 we have been suffering the unprecedented event of COVID 19.   The hospital, and their charity, is working under reduced funding and need our support more than ever.

eventName: Donating Hair for Cancer Research on my 22nd Birthday!
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.


Hello friends! 

Next month I will be celebrating my 22nd birthday in lockdown and was thinking about how to celebrate it. However, it is quite impossible to do so currently during lockdown in a global pandemic. My hair has grown extremely long since the first lockdown and thought I should donate my hair this year as my hair is healthy and of standard for donation (natural, not dyed and/or bleached).

I chose to donate to The Little Princess Trust as they provide free, real-hair wigs for young cancer sufferers or for children and young people experiencing the devastating effects of hair loss. They also fund pioneering, life-saving research into childhood cancers.

I have always been reluctant to cut my hair and I really don’t think I’d ever cut my hair short unless it was for something like this. As a woman, I understand how hair is important to us and I want to share this value to those who are not as fortunate as I am. 

If I have a birthday wish that could come true this year, it is to donate not just my hair but also a donation to help towards cancer research. Birthday gifts and cards are amazing and I am grateful for them, but this year I want to make a real difference and make someone’s day a little brighter. Spreading the love and adding a bit more wonder to the world would mean everything to me! 

I will be sharing pictures of my new hair after the cut, as well as updates of the impact of my fundraising. Until then, please please please consider donating to this very worthy cause!

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
As you may know, Dave had been suffering from bowel and then liver cancer, for a year, and although he had been having chemotherapy, this hadn't suppressed or beaten the liver cancer.  The chemotherapy was stopped four weeks ago, as it wasn't doing any good, and was potentially harming other organs in his body.  Since then, Dave had deteriorated quickly in health, and had become very unwell over the last week.  His quality of life was very minimal, and his passing was a blessing, as we know that he would never recover and become the old Dave.  

As you know, he was a larger than life, noisy character, who always had a funny story or anecdote to tell about any situation, and I think that is what I will miss the most about him.  His ability to make anything, mend anything, or teach anything was one of his most endearing qualities, and I know that many people have thanked him for leading and showing them the way in life, both practically and financially.

I miss my soulmate, lover, best friend, travel companion and out and out good guy, and I cannot contemplate how I will carry on without him, at the moment.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
In December 2019 we were given the devastating news that our beloved Dad had an agrresive brain tumour that would be untreatable. This was more devastating because he had spent the previous 3 years fighting back from a massive stroke. 

Marie curie helped his last weeks become more bearable, they were there for us as well as dad. Made him feel comfortable, cared for and loved. 

Without them we would of struggled much more than we did. He sadly lost that fight on 20th February 2020 and is missed so very much

Thank you for taking the time to read his story x

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story:
Many people that have been diagnosed with diabetes struggle with how to diabetes freedom reviews  and treat it. It is important that they understand that controlling diabetes is not only limited to changing their diet. It also involves a variety of lifestyle changes that they must make, which include following a diabetes diet, using drugs to control diabetes, and managing diabetes symptoms.

One of the first things that you should do is learn more about a diabetes diet. The diabetes diet is different from the typical diabetic diet. It has specific guidelines that will guide you on what you should eat and how much of what. It helps people to develop a healthier lifestyle as well as keep their blood sugar levels under control.

Learning about the diabetes diet can help you with managing your diabetes, whether it is your first diagnosis or your fifth. You need to know how the diet works so that you can be informed on what you can expect when you make changes to your diabetes diet.

In order to avoid losing weight during your diabetes diet, you need to make sure that you find the right diabetes diet that will work for you. This includes choosing one that fits your needs and your current level of diabetes. It can be difficult because there are so many choices, but it is essential that you choose one that is tailored to your lifestyle.

By making sure that you have the proper diabetes diet in place, you will not only be able to manage your diabetes, but you will also be helping others that are struggling with their diabetes as well. Knowing how to control and treat diabetes is the first step toward preventing many complications from developing.

There are two types of diabetes diets that are available to those who have diabetes. These are moderate and extreme. Whichever type you choose, you must remember that each type requires different changes in diet.

In most cases, you can follow a moderate diabetes diet that will help you lose weight and reduce the amount of insulin that you are taking daily. Moderation, however, is not always possible. It is good that you discuss your options with your doctor, as some diets can be rather restrictive.

charity.name: WaterAid
eventName: Paul’s contribution to MCR => MDG with Access & WaterAid
story:
From Manchester to Madagascar 

From 15th February, well be walking, running, cycling, rowing and swimming to travel the 5,777 miles between Manchester to Madagascar, all in aid of highlighting WaterAid's work in Antenanarivo, Madagascar.

5,777 miles might take us a while to complete, so we are going to compete in two teams and start at each end - one team in Manchester and one team in Madagascar - and the objective is to meet in the middle by Easter, and see who gets there first!

Well be walking, running, cycling, rowing or even swimming (when allowed!) to help contribute individually and virtually to the 5,777 miles we need to complete together. 

The objective is to improve all our wellbeing, get us all out more in the fresh air and away from our computers, and to raise £5,777 for a truly magnificent cause!

charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
